      <section class="detail-block">
        <h2>Industry Applications</h2>
        <div class="application-tags">
          <span>Automation Equipment</span>
          <span>Mechanical Assemblies</span>
          <span>Connection Structures</span>
          <span>OEM Components</span>
          <span>Custom Machinery</span>
          <span>Precision Industrial Parts</span>
        </div>
      </section>


      <section class="detail-block">
        <h2>Application Scenarios</h2>
        <div class="scenario-list">
          <div class="scenario-item">
            <h3>Structural Connection in Industrial Machinery Frames</h3>
            <p>Wing connection blocks join structural members in machine frames and support assemblies where the connection point experiences bending loads from multiple directions. Precise CNC milling of the bolt hole pattern, mating faces, and pocket geometry ensures repeatable assembly alignment and the clamping force distribution needed to prevent joint loosening under vibration.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="scenario-item">
            <h3>Automation Equipment Bracket and Support Integration</h3>
            <p>Automation systems require structural brackets that maintain their dimensional relationship under dynamic loads from motors, actuators, and moving payloads. The dimensional accuracy of CNC-milled wing connection blocks ensures that sensor mounts, actuator brackets, and guide rail supports maintain their alignment throughout the service life of the equipment without readjustment.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="scenario-item">
            <h3>Custom Machine Assembly for OEM Applications</h3>
            <p>OEM machinery builders frequently require custom connection blocks for machine-specific structural configurations that standard off-the-shelf hardware cannot address. Drawing-based CNC fabrication of wing connection blocks allows the OEM to specify exactly the geometry needed for their machine's structural requirements, in the right material, without minimum order quantity constraints common in catalogue parts.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="detail-block">
        <h2>CNC Milling Capabilities for Connection Components</h2>
        <p>Connection blocks require accurate hole positioning, flat mating surfaces, and consistent overall dimensions to ensure correct assembly fit across the full production batch. Our CNC milling process holds the dimensional consistency needed for connection components that must assemble interchangeably across multiple machine builds. Send your drawing with tolerance and material requirements to receive a quotation.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="detail-block faq-block">
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-question">What is a wing connection block used for?</h3>
            <p class="faq-answer">A wing connection block is a structural component that joins two or more machine frame members at an angular or orthogonal connection point. The wing geometry provides additional clamping surface area and load distribution compared to a simple bracket, making it suitable for joints that experience bending or vibration loads.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-question">What materials are available for the connection block?</h3>
            <p class="faq-answer">Material is specified according to the drawing and application. Common materials include aluminum alloy, carbon steel, and stainless steel, selected based on load requirements, weight constraints, and environment. We advise on material selection if required.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-question">Can you produce connection blocks to my own drawings?</h3>
            <p class="faq-answer">Yes. We produce all precision machined parts to customer-supplied drawings in DXF, DWG, STEP, IGES, or PDF format. Send your drawing with material specification, tolerance requirements, and quantity for a quotation.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-question">What positional tolerance can you hold for the bolt hole pattern?</h3>
            <p class="faq-answer">Bolt hole positional tolerance depends on the pattern size and material. Typical positional tolerance for CNC-milled hole patterns is ±0.05mm, with tighter tolerances available for critical alignment features. Specify your tolerance requirements in the drawing or contact us to discuss.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-question">Do you offer anodizing or plating for aluminum connection blocks?</h3>
            <p class="faq-answer">Yes. Anodizing is available for aluminum connection blocks for corrosion protection and improved surface hardness. Zinc plating and nickel plating are available for steel components. Surface finish is specified at the order stage.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-question">What batch sizes do you support?</h3>
            <p class="faq-answer">We support prototype quantities (1–10 pieces) through to full batch production. Quantity-appropriate pricing is provided at the quotation stage. Prototype samples are typically produced for dimensional verification before batch runs.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

